 from class F, which can use that item. Because, in the end, there's very little that sets most classes apart.<br>
<br>
All the people saying that disciplines or whatever aren't the same sort of thing are missing the point. They're EXACTLY the same thing. They're what makes those classes special. Leave the specialness alone.<br>
<br>
That's what people are objecting to. We can all argue about something else if you'd prefer, but you can't argue that &quot;disciplines are different than spells&quot; or &quot;items should have procs on them&quot; if what everyone else is asking for is &quot;let my fairly generic class remain special.&quot;<br>
<br>
Ice Comet = Harm Touch = Feign Death skill = ranger Tracking = Defensive discipline = songs = all the rest of the stuff<br>
<br>
It's a motherfucking game. And people play the motherfucking game because it's supposed to be fucking fun. When the designers start picking the fucking pockets of one player to give new special treats to another, it makes that first player feel like, shit, what made his play experience fun has gone away a little.<br>
<br>
Now, we could play a classless game, where everyone gets all things, but that's not EQ as it was designed. We have Asheron's Call, Dungeon Seige and even, to a large extent, the original Diablo if we want to play that way. If you really think specialness and uniqueness isn't all that important, I strongly urge you to check out those three games, since they do much better with that concept than EQ ever will.<br>
<br>
In the meantime, understand that many, perhaps even most people playing EQ like the specialness and want to keep their motherfucking specialness for themselves, OK?<br>
<br>
Next person who says that Defensive disc or whatever doesn't count gets kicked in the nuts and forced to re-read this over and over again until you understand you're missing the motherfucking point?<br>
